  "text": "The limitations of our study are several. First, our survival rate comparison did not have a temporal replicate. Such replicates must now wait until any residual evolutionary effects of the released fish have decayed back to near the starting condition. Second, our sample sizes were relatively small, which was necessitated by the very small populations at the time of our experiment. Thus, we likely have good estimates of population parameters, but these parameters may be influenced by random variation owing to small population size. Third, our overall experiment has been unreplicated in the sense that we examined only a single experimental introduction (Yarra to Damier), and so our inferences are specific to that context. Ideally, we would now replicate our study in another population and site. This limitation, however, also applies to other studies examining the survival consequences of adaptation to altered environments in nature (e.g., [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Evolutionary biologists are still at such an early stage in addressing this particular question that demonstrations for single populations remain extremely important.",
